'''Maureen Dowd''' (born January 14, 1952) is an [[Americans|American]] columnist for ''[[The New York Times]]''. She is also a best-selling [[author]]. She worked for [[Time (magazine)|''Time'' magazine]] in the 1970s and 1980s. She worked for the ''Washington Star''. She first joined ''The New York Times'' in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maureen Dowd|publisher=Pulitzer Prizes|url=http://www.pulitzer.org/biography/1999-Commentary|accessdate=Mar 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Maureen Dowd|publisher=The New York Times|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210074418/http://topics.nytimes.com/ref/opinion/DOWD-BIO.html|accessdate=Mar 5, 2015}}</ref>

In 1999, Dowd received a [[Pulitzer Prize]].<ref name=Pulitzer>{{cite web | url=http://www.pulitzer.org/citation/1999-Commentary | title=The 1999 Pulitzer Prize Winners: Commentary: Citation | publisher=Columbia University | accessdate=Mar 5, 2015 }}</ref> It was for her series of columns on the [[Lewinsky scandal|Monica Lewinsky scandal]] in the [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]] administration.<ref name=Pulitzer/>

She was born in [[Washington, D.C.]].

